red        =\n|website        = [http://www.sorellefanchini.it/ sorellefanchini.it]\n|olympicteams   = 2 \u2013 ([[Alpine skiing at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006]], [[Alpine skiing at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010]])\n|olympicmedals  = 0\n|olympicgolds   = \n|worldsteams    = 4 \u2013 ([[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2005|2005]], [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2007|'07]], [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2011|'11]], [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2013|'13]])\n|worldsmedals   = 1\n|worldsgolds    = 0\n|wcseasons      = 13 \u2013 ([[2005 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2005]]\u2013[[2008 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2008]], [[2010 Alpine Skiing World Cup|10]]\u2013[[2018 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2018]])\n|wcwins         = 2 \u2013 (2 DH)             \n|wcpodiums      = 4 \u2013 (4 DH) \n|wcoveralls     = 0 \u2013 ''(17th in [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2015]])''\n|wctitles       = 0 \u2013 ''(5th in [[Downhill (ski competition)|DH]], [[2015 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2015]])''\n|show-medals    = yes\n|medals         = \n{{Medal|Competition|World Cup race podiums}}\n{{MedalCount | total = yes\n| Downhill | 2 | 0 | 2\n}}\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[alpine skiing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{ITA}} }}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2005|2005 Bormio]]|[[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships 2005|Downhill]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Fanchini''' (born 30 April 1985<!-- in [[Lovere]]-->) is a former [[Alpine skiing|alpine ski racer]] from [[Italy]]. She was born and lives in [[Val Camonica]], she focused on the speed events of [[downhill (ski competition)|downhill]] and [[super-G]]. Her younger sisters [[Nadia Fanchini|Nadia]] and [[Sabrina Fanchini|Sabrina]] also raced on the Italian team.<ref name=efpupse>{{cite web|url=http://www.fis-ski.com/alpine-skiing/news-multimedia/news/article=elena-fanchini-picks-second-career-win-cortina.html |publisher= FIS-Ski.com |title=Elena Fanchini picks up second career win in Cortina |date=16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nFanchini won two World Cups in downhill 9 years apart and won a silver medal at the 2005 world championships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/skiing/story/_/id/22075007/italian-skier-elena-fanchini-treating-tumor-ends-season|title=Italian skier Fanchini treating tumor, ends season|date=2018-01-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref name=surphtc>{{cite journal |url=http://skiracing.com/stories/fanchini-surprises-hometown-crowd-in-cortina-downhill/ |magazine=Ski Racing |title=Fanchini surprises hometown crowd in Cortina downhill |last=Kelley |first=Jessica |date=16 January 2015}}</ref> She represented Italy at two [[Alpine skiing at the Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] and four [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.fis-ski.com/global-links/statistics/competitors-having-more-than-one-podium.html?place=&season=ALL&sector=AL&nbr=4&gender=M&category=WC&positions=2&nation=&discipline=ALL&Submit=SEARCH|title=COMPETITORS HAVING MORE THAN ONE PODIUM|publisher=fis-ski.com|accessdate=3 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204000231/https://data.fis-ski.com/global-links/statistics/competitors-having-more-than-one-podium.html?place=&season=ALL&sector=AL&nbr=4&gender=M&category=WC&positions=2&nation=&discipline=ALL&Submit=SEARCH|archive-date=4 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.fis-ski.com/global-links/statistics/competitors-having-more-than-one-podium.html?place=&sea|title=COMPETITORS HAVING MORE THAN ONE TOP 10 POSITION|publisher=fis-ski.com|accessdate=4 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072206/https://data.fis-ski.com/global-links/statistics/competitors-having-more-than-one-podium.html?place=&sea|archive-date=5 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Cancer==\nOn 12 January 2018 Fanchini announced that she would have to give up participating in the [[Pyeongchang]] [[2018 Winter Olympics]] in order to undergo [[cancer]] treatment. In the 2019 season she was preparing to return to the World Cup, but during training for the [[Killington, Vermont|Killington]] [[Super-G]] she fell on the Superstar track and suffered a fracture of a finger of the hand and a distortion-bruising trauma to the left [[knee]], with fracture of the proximal fibula. The injury forced her to return to [[Italy]] without being able to compete in the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/sports/2018/11/23/skiingelena-fanchini-quits-after-injury_6f0dda00-8594-407e-a62a-b5d239f55dcb.html|title=Skiing:Elena Fanchini quits after injury|quote=Downhill specialist had recently returned after beating cancer|publisher=ansa.it|date=23 November 2018|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2020 Elena and her sister Nadia both announced their retirement from alpine skiing.\n\n==World Cup results==\n===Season standings===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Season !! Age !! &nbsp;Overall&nbsp; !! &nbsp;Slalom&nbsp; !! Giant<br>&nbsp;slalom&nbsp; !! Super-G !! Downhill !!Combined\n|-\n| [[2005 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2005]] || ''19'' || 75 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 45 || 32 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2006 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2006]] || ''20'' || 41 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 47 || 12 || \u2014 \n|-\n| [[2007 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2007]] || ''21'' || 77 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 50 || 30 || \u2014 \n|-\n| [[2008 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2008]] || ''22'' || 45 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 34 || 23 || 39\n|-\n| [[2009 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2009]] || ''23'' || \u2014 || \u2014  || \u2014 || \u2014  || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n| [[2010 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2010]] || ''24'' || 53 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 26 || 24 || \u2014 \n|-\n| [[2011 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2011]] || ''25'' || 28 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 25 || 12 || \u2014 \n|-\n| [[2012 Alpine Skiing World Cup|2012]] || ''26'' || 36 || \u2014 || \u