6415}}\n* [https://www.fis-ski.com/DB/general/athlete-biography.html?sectorcode=AL&competitorid=16415&type=cups Elena Fanchini] World Cup standings at the International Ski Federation\n* {{Ski-db|elena_fanchini_ita_296472}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile}}\n* {{official website|http://www.sorellefanchini.it/}} ''{{in lang|it}}'' (Fanchini Sisters)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanchini, Elena}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Bergamo]]\n[[Category:Italian female alpine skiers]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2006 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic alpine skiers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers of Fiamme Gialle]]\n[[Category:Alpine skiers at the 2014 Winter Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Marbe166", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elena_Fanchini"}
{"title_page": "Dulce Pinzon", "text_new": "[[File:Dulce_Pinz\u00f3n_cropped.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Dulce Pinzon]]\n'''Dulce Pinz\u00f3n''' (born 1974, Mexico City, [[Mexico]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://especiales.univision.com/desigualdad/profile/dulce-pinzon/1045|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n - Desigualdad. Univision|website=especiales.univision.com|language=es|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712210919/http://especiales.univision.com/desigualdad/profile/dulce-pinzon/1045|archive-date=2018-07-12|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelift.mx/news/people-of-mexico-local-photographer-dulce-pinzon|title=People of Mexico: Local Photographer, Dulce Pinz\u00f3n|website=The Lift|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] artist currently living in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]], and [[Mexico City]], Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/latino/musica-y-recuerdos-article-1.315319|title=M\u00fasica y recuerdos|last=Alvarado|first=Virginia|date=|website=New York Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> In 2015 she was named by [[Forbes|Forbes Magazine]] as \"One of the 50 most creative Mexicans in the world\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com.mx/los-50-mexicanos-mas-creativos-en-el-mundo/|title=Los 50 mexicanos m\u00e1s creativos en el mundo \u2022 Forbes M\u00e9xico|last=Staff|first=Forbes|date=2015-12-15|website=Forbes M\u00e9xico|language=es-MX|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> and [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Magazine]] identified her as one of the \"8 Mexican female photographers who are breaking through at a global level.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.mx/estilo-de-vida/branded/8-fotografas-mexicanas-que-la-estan-rompiendo-a-nivel-mundial|title=8 fot\u00f3grafas mexicanas que la est\u00e1n rompiendo a nivel mundial|website=Vogue Mexico|language=es-MX|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n==Education==\nPinz\u00f3n studied Mass Media Communications at the [[Universidad de las Am\u00e9ricas Puebla|Universidad de Las Am\u00e9ricas Puebla]] in Mexico, and Photography at [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania]] in the United States .<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpw.org/past-exhibitions/dulce-pinzon/|title=CPW \u2014 Dulce Pinz\u00f3n|last=|first=|date=2007-11-12|website=The Center for Photography at Woodstock|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> She moved to [[New York City]] in 1995 and studied at the [[International Center of Photography]]. She lives and works in Mexico and New York.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://museoamparo.com/artistas/perfil/388/dulce-pinzon|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n {{!}} Artistas {{!}} Museo Amparo, Puebla|last=MuseoAmparo.Puebla|website=museoamparo.com|language=es|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Photography ==\nPinzon's work is influenced by feelings of nostalgia, questions of identity, and political, and cultural frustrations.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />  The goal that she pursues through her art activism is cultural consumption, customization, and intervention. Some of her projects are: \"Viviendo En El [[Gabacho]]\"(a Spanish colloquialism for \"foreign\" which in Mexico is used as a Mexican colloquialism for \"living in the United States\"),<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.galeriadelaraza.org/eng/exhibits2/archive/artists.php?op=view&id=512&media=info|title=Galer\u00eda de la Raza: Dulce Pinz\u00f3n|website=www.galeriadelaraza.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \"[[Loter\u00eda|Loteria]]\" (Lottery), \"Multiracial\", and \"Real Stories of Superheroes.\" Her work has been published and exhibited in Mexico, the United States, [[Australia]], [[Latin America]], [[Asia]], and [[Europe]].<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/batman-superman-y-la-mujer-maravilla-hacen-trabajos-de-latinos-nid1534578|title=Batman, Superman y la Mujer Maravilla hacen trabajos de latinos|last=|first=|date=2012-12-07|website=La Nacion Newspaper|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.es/20121112/cultura-arte/abci-dulce-pinzon-exposicion-201211121544.html|title=As\u00ed son los superh\u00e9roes (de carne y hueso) en EE.UU.|last=|first=|date=2012-11-12|website=ABC Madrid|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n===The Real Story of the Superheroes===\nIn 2006, Pinz\u00f3n completed a project in which she photographed several immigrant workers in New York City dressed as superheroes<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Schwendener|first=Martha|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/31/arts/design/31muse.html|title=A Latino Biennial That Bucks a Global Trend|date=2007-08-31|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/slideshow/the-magnificent-migrants/|title=The Magnificent Migrants|last=Pinz\u00f3n|first=Dulce|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> who, like her, mostly originally came from the state of [[Puebla]] in Mexico. \u201cThey\u2019re so quiet and hard-working and invisible\u201d, Pinz\u00f3n said of her subjects in a feature article in ''The New York Times'' in 2006.<ref name=\":1\" /> \u201cI wanted to pay a tribute to them.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Murphy|first=Tim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/24/nyregion/thecity/24hero.html|title=Hombres of Steel|date=2006-09-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Pinz\u00f3n drew on her nostalgia for Mexicopop culture as a medium to get her views across to through her art.<ref>Fokuslimonta.wordpress.com/2008/02/27/la-verdadera-historia-de-los-superheroes/</ref> \n\nThis series consists of 20 color photographs of Mexican immigrants dressed in the costumes of well-known American and Mexican superheroes.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://alidaanderson.com/Artists/DulcePinzon/DulcePinzon.html|title=Dulce Pinzon - Represented by Alida Anderson Art Projects|website=alidaanderson.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/photog-captures-super-heroics-immigs-article-1.1199813|title=Photographer Dulce Pinzon portrays immigrants as superheroes, showing off their successes with flying colors|last=FEIDEN|first=DOUGLAS|date=|website=New York Daily News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Pinz\u00f3n breaks down the photographs' titles into five sections which not only title the photographs, but also deliver biographical data about the subject.<ref name=\":4\" /> These sections are:\n\n* Name of the superhero\n* Name of the daily worker\n* Name of their home country\n* What the laborer does for a living\n* And the amount of money that they send home. \n\nOne example of these \"everyday superheroes\" is the photograph titled ''\"Noe Reyes. He sends hundreds of dollars back to Mexico every month.\"''<ref name=\":3\" /> There are many undocumented workers from Puebla who reside in New York City and who work as dishwashers, deli workers, and cleaning women, etc. and whom are rarely recognized for their everyday acts of sacrifice and heroism in supporting their families in their countries of origin.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trendhunter.com/trends/dulce-pinzon|title=Everyday Hero Shoots|last=Hinkson|first=Ralph|date=2009-11-06|website=TrendHunter.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> \n\nAnother example, is the story of behind the photograph Minerva Valencia,<ref name=\":6\" /> who dressed up as [[Catwoman]] for Dulce's artwork.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telerama.fr/scenes/dulce-pinzon,-la-photographe-qui-transforme-les-immigres-mexicains-en-super-heros,n6405870.php|title=Dulce Pinzon, la photographe qui transforme les immigr\u00e9s mexicains en superh\u00e9ros|last=Rossignol|first=Lorraine|date=2019-06-09|website=T\u00e9l\u00e9rama|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Valencia came to New York from [[Puebla (city)|Puebla]] and works as a babysitter in New York. The amount of economic remittance that she sends back to Puebla, Mexico is four hundred dollars per week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kunsthaus.org.mx/Dulce/biografia_ing.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724150755/http://www.kunsthaus.org.mx/Dulce/biografia_ing.htm |archive-date=2011-07-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n[[The New Yorker|''The'' ''New Yorker'' magazine]] photography critic Maria Lokke wrote about these images:<blockquote>In Dulce Pinzon\u2019s \u201cSuperheroes\u201d series, costumes are superimposed on working-class Mexicans in New York: cooks, nannies, construction workers. These satirical scenes question modern heroism and bring into focus the vital role these individuals play in the lives of their families and in the economy of the larger community, on both sides of the border. She made these pictures, she writes, \u201cto pay homage to these brave and determined men and women that somehow manage, without the help of any supernatural power, to withstand extreme conditions of labor in order to help their families and communities survive and prosper.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/photo-booth/mexico-afuera-at-aperture|title=Mexico + Afuera, at Aperture|last=Lokke|first=Maria|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref></blockquote>And in discussing Pinzon's photographs at the [[Art Museum of the Americas]], [[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian magazine]] observed that :<blockquote>The iconic \u201cReal Stories of Superheroes\u201d series by Brooklyn-based Mexican photographer Dulce Pinz\u00f3n depicts Mexican immigrants in the service sector performing their daily tasks while disguised as American superheroes. With titles such as \u201cAquaman is Juventino Rosas From the State of Mexico. He Works in a Fish Market in New York. He Sends $400 Home Each Week,\u201d the portraits memorialize the accomplishments of an enormous but invisible population.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2012/03/09/art-review-ew-york-at-the-art-museum-of-the-americas/|title=Art Review: \u201c\u00d1ew York\u201d at the Art Museum of the Americas {{!}} Washingtonian (DC)|last=Shook|first=Beth|date=2012-03-09|website=Washingtonian Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> </blockquote>This project is easily Pinzon's best-known series and has been exhibited worldwide in museums, galleries and international art fairs.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Brook|first=Pete|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/09/dulce-pinzon/|title=Photog Gives Migrant Workers the Superhero Treatment|date=2010-09-14|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-21|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mutualart.com/Artist/Dulce-Pinzon/B981967B43F9E35C/Biography|title=Pinz\u00f3n, Dulce {{!}} Biography|website=www.mutualart.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/media/2008/04/mexican-superheroes-dulce-pinzon/|title=Mexican Superheroes|last=Pinzon|first=Dulce|website=Mother Jones|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/immigration/2015/02/05/migrant-superheroes-honoured-in-dulce-pinzon-photos.html|title=#MigrantHeroes honoured in Dulce Pinzon photos|last=Keung|first=Nicolas|date=2015-02-05|website=The Star Newspaper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://txcontemporary.com/exhibitors/exhibitor/alida-anderson-art-projects-texas-contemporary-2016|title=Texas Contemporary {{!}}|website=Texas Contemporary|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/ev--zia-gallery-presents-dulce-pinzn-and-maggie-meiners|title=ZIA Gallery presents Dulce Pinz\u00f3n and Maggie Meiners|date=2012-06-08|website=Winnetka-Glencoe, IL Patch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://artworldchicago.com/tag/dulce-pinzon/|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n|website=Art World Chicago|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The process taken by Pinz\u00f3n in her art photographic activism was cultural consumption (superheroes), customization (Mexican laborers portrayed as superheroes), and intervention (art displayed in mainstream areas such as museums, galleries and art fairs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://contemporaryartumd.artinterp.org/omeka/dulce-pinzn-the-real-story-of-the-superheroes-20042005|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n, \"The real story of the Superheroes,\" 2004\u20132005 \u00b7 Contemporary Art Purchasing Program - Stamp Gallery|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Maryland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Inspired by these photographs, in 2015 the Geneva-based [[International Organization for Migration (IOM) Mission in Ukraine|International Organization for Migration]] (IOM) launched a social media campaign under the tag #MigrantHeroes \"to invite people around the world to identify and tell the stories of migrant heroes.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 2012 the photographic series was published in English, Spanish and French as a book titled ''Dulce Pinz\u00f3n: The Real Story of the Superheroes'' (Editorial RM, {{ISBN|978-8415118244}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/culture/state-of-the-art-your-weekly-guide-to-nyc-latino-art-openings/|title=State of the Art: Your Weekly Guide to NYC's Latino Art Openings {{!}} Art, Culture|date=2013-03-25|website=Remezcla|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" />\n\n===Loteria===\nAs it has been noted in academic research on her work,<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Bayly|first=Heather Jane|date=2013-10-16|title=Professional Wrestling and Contemporary Photography: The Case of Dulce Pinz\u00f3n\u2019s The Real Story of the Superheroes|url=http://journals.openedition.org/rrca/527|journal=Revue de recherche en civilisation am\u00e9ricaine|language=fr|issue=4|issn=2101-048X}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Desai|first=Dipti|date=2010|title=Unframing Immigration: Looking Through the Educational Space of Contemporary Art|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25759042|journal=Peabody Journal of Education|volume=85|issue=4|pages=425\u2013442|doi=10.2307/25759042|issn=0161-956X}}</ref> Dulce Pinzon's work is also clearly inspired by the dualistic culture within Mexicans in New York.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> She demonstrated this concept of dualism in her 2001-2002 project \"[[Loter\u00eda|Loteria]]\" (Spanish for \"Lottery\"), which is a traditional Mexican card game. In this project, she used the card images from this well known Mexican card game, and projected these images onto the nude bodies of some of her New York friends and loved ones.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nagarimagazine.com/nagari-entrevista-a-la-fotografa-mexicana-dulce-pinzon/|title=NAGARI ENTREVISTA A LA FOT\u00d3GRAFA MEXICANA DULCE PINZ\u00d3N|last=|first=|date=2013-08-31|website=Nagari Magazine|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> This project is also representative of the [[Cubans|Cuban]] scholar [[Fernando Ortiz Fern\u00e1ndez]] concept of [[transculturation]].<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-autrepart-2013-4-page-281.htm|title=La v\u00e9ritable histoire des superh\u00e9ros|last=Kand\u00e9|first=Sylvie|date=2014-09-16|website=Cairn Info|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> By projecting the images of the cards of the \"Loteria\" game onto the human bodies of New York residents, she demonstrated how culture [[counter-flows]] through people's migration patterns, which is a form of [[cultural remittances]].<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n=== Multiracial ===\nFunded by a grant from the Mexican National Fund for Art and Culture (FONCA),<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://dodgeburnphoto.com/2008/02/photo-project-dulce-pinzons-multiracial/|title=Photo Project: Dulce Pinz\u00f3n's \"Multiracial\"|last=Mestrich|first=Qiana|date=2008-02-12|website=Dodge & Burn: Decolonizing Photography History|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> this photographic portrait project<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parainmigrantes.info/dulce-pizon-galeria-multiracial/|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n. Galer\u00eda Multiracial.|date=2008-09-10|website=Parainmigrantes|language=es|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> consists of 16 color portraits of \"people of mixed ethnic origin in front of primary color backgrounds.\"<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fotofestin.com/dulce-pinzon/|title=El mensaje social de Dulce Pinz\u00f3n|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Alan|date=2015-06-30|website=Fotofest\u00edn|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> This work has been described as: \"Mexican-born New Yorker Dulce Pinzon, in her \"Multiracial\" series, revisits the bold color fields characteristic of traditional Latin American art and reinterprets them as brilliant backgrounds for explorations into what color means for an increasingly diverse society, evermore concerned with self-identity.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.risaneedlemangallery.com/exhibitions.htm|title=Contemporary Latin American Art Group Show|last=Needleman|first=Risa|date=2005-06-01|website=Risa Needleman Gallery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n== Awards ==\n2014-2017 - Endowment of the Arts SNCA/FONCA Fellowship, Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.envisionkindness.org/judges/|title=Judges - PHOTO '17 Contest|last=|first=|date=|website=Envision Kindness|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n2012 - First Place Award - Sixth International Photography Symposium: Mazatl\u00e1n Abierto, Mexico<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rencontres-arles.com//en/artistes/view/579/|title=Dulce Pinzon|last=|first=|date=|website=Les Rencontres de la Photographie d'Arles|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2011 - ZONAMACO Perrier Art Prize for Digital Photography, Mexico City, Mexico<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arteporexcelencias.com/en/news/2011-04-18/2011-zonamaco-prizes.html|title=2011 ZONAMACO Prizes {{!}} Arte por Excelencias|website=www.arteporexcelencias.com|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2010 - Gaea Foundation/Sea Change Residency Award<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n2008 - Ford Foundation Grant<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/sanantonio/the-secret-lives-of-superheroes/Content?oid=2282258|title=The secret lives of superheroes|last=Herrera|first=Jennifer|website=San Antonio Current|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2006 - New York Foundation for the Arts Fellowship in Photography<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n2002 - J\u00f3venes Creadores Grant, Mexico<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esopus.org/contents/view/181|title=ESOPUS Magazine : Contents|website=www.esopus.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2002 - Mexican National Fund for Art and Culture grant<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n==Selected Exhibitions==\n2006 - Dulce Pinzon - ''The Real Story of the Superheroes -'' Queens Museum, New York, NY, USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://queensmuseum.org/2015/12/dulce-pinzon|title=Dulce Pinzon - The Real Story of the Superheroes|last=|first=|date=2006-07-21|website=Queens Museum|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n2007 - 2008: Kunsthaus [[Miami]], [[Florida]], United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timconnor.blogspot.com/2007/11/|title=Tim Connor|website=timconnor.blogspot.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Jesus|first=Carlos Suarez De|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/immigrants-are-superheroes-6332513|title=Immigrants Are Superheroes|date=2008-01-31|work=Miami New Times|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n\n2008 -''The Real Story of Superheroes'' - Dicke Building Art Gallery at [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]], [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]]<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n2008 - ''A Declaration of Immigration'' - National Museum of Mexican Art, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nationalmuseumofmexicanart.org/exhibits/declaration-immigration|title=A Declaration of Immigration {{!}} National Museum of Mexican Art|website=nationalmuseumofmexicanart.org|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n2011 - Fotogr\u00e1fica de Bogot\u00e1, [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://centrodelaimagen.wordpress.com/2011/05/23/superheroes-de-dulce-pinzon-en-fotografica-de-bogota/|title=Superh\u00e9roes, de Dulce Pinz\u00f3n en Fotogr\u00e1fica de Bogot\u00e1|last=centrodelaimagen|date=2011-05-23|website=Centro de la Imagen|language=es-ES|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n2011 - Pittsburgh Biennial, [[The Andy Warhol Museum]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n2011- 'Les Rencontres d'Arles Photographie Festival, [[Arles]], [[France]]<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.claudinecolin.com/en/613-the-recontres-d-arles-photography-festival|title=THE RENCONTRES D'ARLES - PHOTOGRAPHY FESTIVAL - Arles, France|website=www.claudinecolin.com|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n2011 - ''Dulce Pinz\u00f3n: Superheroes'' - [[Foosaner Art Museum]], [[Melbourne, Florida|Melbourne]], Florida, USA<ref name=\":7\" /> \n\n2012 - \u201c\u00d1ew York\u201d, [[Art Museum of the Americas]], Washington, DC, USA<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/1313175/0/new-york/exposicion/artistas-iberoamericanos/|title=Artistas iberoamericanos muestran sus obras basadas en la Gran Manzana en '\u00d1ew York'|last=EFE|first=|date=2012-02-18|website=www.20minutos.es - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> \n\n2013 - LATINO/US Cotidiano, [[Museum of Latin American Art]], Long Beach, California, USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/article24748597.html|title=\u2018Latino/US Cotidiano\u2019 exhibit breaks boundaries of stereotypes|last=Recio|first=Maria|date=2019-04-29|website=McClatchy Newspapers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2013/10/18/no-superheroes-in-molaas-3-new-exhibitions/|title=No superheroes in MOLAA\u2019s 3 new exhibitions|date=2013-10-18|website=Orange County Register|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2013 - Double Portraits, [[San Diego Museum of Art]], San Diego, California, USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sdmart.org/exhibition/double-portraits/|title=Double Portraits|website=San Diego Museum of Art|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n2013 - Character Study, [[DeCordova Museum and Sculpture Park]], Lincoln, [[Massachusetts]], USA                                        \n\n2013 - ''The Real Story of Superheroes -'' [[Boca Raton Museum of Art]], [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]], Florida, USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bocamuseum.org/exhibitions/dulce-pinz%C3%B3n-real-story-superheroes-0|title=Dulce Pinz\u00f3n: The Real Story of the Superheroes|last=inga.ford|date=2015-12-02|website=Boca Raton Museum of Art|language=en|access-